An object is composed of PLSVO :
(POINTS, LINES, SURFACES, VOLUMES, OBJECTS).
A PLSVO is defined by its type P L S V ou O.
A PLSVO has a NAME known by the User.

The VOLUMES are the MATERIALS.
At each MATERIAL are ASSOCIATED PHYSICAL CHARACTERISTICS.

The SURFACES, LINES, POINTS support the BOUNDARY CONDITIONS
for the problems to solve on this object.

In 2D or axisymmetric, the MATERIALS are the SURFACES
and PL support the boundary conditions.

Example in 3D:       
5; { OBJETS PARTIES DE L OBJET }
 JAW; {NAME DE L'OBJET}
 0;  { CLASSICAL 2D or 3D }
 5;  { NBDOBJ NUMBER of POINTS LINES SURFACES VOLUMES OBJECTS of the OBJECT}
 V; MECHANICAL_PIECE; {NTYOBJ(1..NBDOBJ) 'TYPE of PLSVO NAME and PLSVO NAME}
 SURFACE; RIGHT_WASHER;
 S; LEFT_WASHER;
 S; CYLINDER_WITH_FORCE;
 S; RAIL_FIXED;
 @;
7; { INTERPOLATION DEFINITION of MESH NODES}
 JAW; 4; { LAGRANGE of DEGREE 2 }
@;

Example in axisymmetric:
5;{ OBJECTS components of the OBJECT }
 WATER_CASTLE;  0;  {classic solution 2D or 3D with renumbering}
 5; { number of Points Lines Surfaces Volumes Objects of the object}
 SURFACE; GROUND;
 S; CONCRETE;
 L; D2E2;
 L; D1D2;
 L; DISPLNULL;
@;
7; { Interpolation }
 WATER_CASTLE;
 2; {AXISYMETRIC LAGRANGE DEGREE 2}
@;
